{
  "texts": [
    "A total of 370 references were coded, averaging 1.2 per respondent (Appendix Table 2).",
    "Most of the responses (n = 233) were classified as Performance Expectancy, that is, respondents were motivated to change how and what they will teach due to the belief that AI will assist them, and their students, in their future performance.",
    "Interestingly, the most frequent responses were about their students' future performance rather than their own.",
    "Over one-third of participants were motivated by the performance expectancy of their students (n = 136), commenting that AI would \"enhance student learning\", give them \"an authentic learning experience\", and provide them \"knowledge and skills\".",
    "A sense of urgency in the lexicon was apparent: educators concerned that their students were \"not missing out\", \"need to be made aware\" or \"have to be ready\" for an AI-integrated future."
  ]
}